A matter of perspective. 
cc: @karimiliya

Six essential strategies to achieve a film-like aesthetic in your images and an editing breakdown from start to finish to keep developing your style! With @harrysohalphoto / ‚ÄúWhat inspires me most in photography is finding beauty in unexpected places. I‚Äôve learned beauty isn‚Äôt about perfection but authenticity and raw emotion. By focusing on composition, color, and lighting, each image becomes more than a picture - it‚Äôs part of a larger story: 

1) My workflow begins with envisioning the concept and gathering inspiration. I create mood boards on Pinterest and let the ideas marinate for a few days. 

2) Once the concept is finalized, I seek models who can bring my vision to life. Then, I try to capture the perfect light and mood, usually resulting in about 70-80 carefully crafted shots.¬†I start the culling process immediately to keep the concept fresh.

3) For editing, I adjust the colors to match the desired vibe and refine the image with detailed touch-ups and masking techniques - you can find an example from start to finish in this carousel. 

4) The tone curve is my favorite tool to achieve a film-like aesthetic. It‚Äôs essential for fine-tuning contrast and tonal range. In addition, I like the dehaze slider to balance highlights and shadows,¬†and the grain and noise tools help me add texture, creating that classic film look that gives photos a tactile, organic feel. 

5) Warm tones, like oranges and yellows, are integral to my style, evoking a sense of warmth, nostalgia, and vibrancy. I often shoot during golden hour, which naturally provides these colors, and in post-processing, I enhance them to emphasize the inherent warmth and depth in my images.

6) My last advice to aspiring photographers is to practice consistently. Immerse yourself, edit the same image differently, and learn from each experience. 

The more you experiment, the more you develop your unique style and ability to capture stunning images. Remember, the key to compelling photography is not just in the perfect shot but in the emotion, authenticity, and story it tells!‚Äù You can read the original article with @harrysohalphoto by visiting the link in our bio!

A bite-sized look at @mariyahnoor123's photography #MadewithLightroom 

"I do food photography as a hobby and I love to capture the beauty of food in natural light. I believe evoking emotions is key to grabbing the viewer's attention. As for any photography editing plays a crucial role in bringing out the subtle details of a subject. Lightroom has been an indispensable tool for this purpose. 

This definitely is my go-to editing app for its versatility and convenience. I love how I can do precise adjustments with the help of the masking tool. The non-destructive editing gives immense flexibility which is particularly valuable in food photography where fine-tuning makes a significant difference. The best thing about Lightroom is that despite its powerful features, it has a user-friendly interface."

This is SS Polynesian wreck just south of Malta. This huge vessel measures 152,5m and weighted 6700 gross tonnes. She was built near Marseille, France in 1890. SS Polynesian was a passenger ship armed with canons both in the bow and stern. The ship was sunk by the German submarine SM UC-22 on 10 august 1918. 17 people where killed during the battle. The wreck today rests on a slight port side angle at the depth of 68m and is a fantastic wreck-dive

In the wild, our skills, intelligence, wealth, and perceived superiority as humans are irrelevant. Here, our societal rules, opinions, and moral codes hold no weight. When all cultural and material trappings are removed, leaving our essence bare, we realize that humanity is just a small component of a far grander entity. This is why I love rhinos; I cherish the feeling of insignificance they inspire. Their powerful presence vividly illustrates my humble position within the natural order.
